4. Short Write-Up
Proposed Features
1.Alert Inbox with Priority Indicators
 Helps engineers focus on the most critical alerts first. Filtering reduces noise.

2.Detailed Alert View with Context
 Gives the full picture: what happened, where it happened, and why it matters.
 This reduces investigation time.

3.Guided Remediation Flow
 Provides a safe, clear way to review and apply fixes.
 Engineers gain confidence by seeing the impact before applying changes.


Why These Features Were Prioritized
●High Priority: Alert Details + Context
 This is the main place where decisions are made. Providing rich context reduces investigation time and false positives.

●Medium Priority: Inbox Filters
 Helps navigate large volumes of alerts but can be improved over time.

●Medium Priority: Remediation Workflow
 Important for completing the alert lifecycle but can be built after the context view is solid.

●Lower Priority: Impact Simulation
 A helpful advanced feature but not essential for minimal viable product.

The focus is on clarity, speed, and reducing mental load for the security engineer.

Success Metrics
1.Reduction in Time to Triage an Alert
 Target: 30–50% faster decision-making.

2.Increase in Alerts Investigated and Resolved
 Higher closure rates show improved usability.

3.Decrease in False Positives Marked by Engineers
 Better context leads to fewer misjudged alerts.

4.User Satisfaction & Feedback
 Engineers should report less alert fatigue and greater confidence.

5.Adoption and Usage Data
 More active users and repeated use indicate that the workflow is effective.

